everything about the Pines of Rome is deceptive:  the place looks very ordinary but the owner purchases the very best ingredients, including rare items such as goose, and really fresh, wild caught seafood--a great rarity in the Washington area where fashionable restaurants mostly serve farm-raised rubbish listed under fake Mediterranean names. The waiters mostly look like construction workers but are actually very attentive. Even the clientele is deceptive--it is the place where the very richest people in the Washington area come in the most informal clothes they own. The owner too is deceptive: seeing him popping  out of the kitchen now & then with his baseball hat none could possibly guess that he is a formidable romance-language scholar perfectly at home in  proto-Castilian poetry, the Cervantes canon beyond  Don Qixote & others such,. And yes, the food is very good especially if you choose the white over the red.As for authenticity:  io sono cresciuto in Italia, e so la differenza fra la vera cucina Italiana e le imitazioni.

I'm vegan and was told by a waiter that the eggplant parm could be made as such. I specifically said no cheese, multiple times. They agreed and said that they understood exactly how to make it; that it was "no problem". I walked a mile to get there and a mile back. When I reached the office, I realized that they had covered the eggplant parm in cheese and had not at all listened to what we had discussed. Upon this discovery, I called them and asked if they could right their wrongs by delivering the corrected item. They said that they couldn't; they "didn't have drivers available" (note that they do deliveries and have cars to do so). I told them then that I wanted a refund on my credit card then. They acted like they couldn't do it at first until I came all the way back. I said I didn't have time because I was at work. They finally took my card number and assured me that it would be done by EOB. But of course, it's the next day and it's still not there. Terrible customer service - and the food, from my friend who ordered as well, was 'decent at best.' Needless to say, we won't be going back.

Pines of Rome is my favorite restaurant on the entire planet! My family has been going here for over 40 years and I have been going since I was young enough to remember! The white pizza is to die for it is so amazingly rich and gooey. When I think of pines of Rome I think of family and more than just family, my Italian heritage. You go there for the food and the food makes you feel good. I literally go to pines every time I am in town (I now live in Kentucky). The food and service, was sub-par. To be honest I hadn’t come here in a really long time, but I had to return the food because it was awful. The tomato “sauce was like they opened a can of while tomatoes and put on the pasta. The marsala tasted metallic and as if they had added lemon. Not to mention that they brought the main dish while we were starting to eat the appetizer, on a small table for a party of four and the servers were annoyed because there was no room on the table. I hope they bring everything back to the wonderful place this used to be.

I am always amazed when I read "Best Italian Food!" Because any REAL italian wouldn't be caught dead in this place!!! The picture itself shows pasta with Stewed tomatoes as their Marinara sauce. There is nothing italian about it. The service is spotty at best and the food subpar. How this place managed to stay in business so long while there are now some mom and pop cooking REAL italian food blows my mind.  I went there with a large group of friends from Milan, one a chef, who had read a few reviews here and thought it might be good. If we had not been laughing so much when they brought out their "Authentic Italian dishes" the night would have been a total bust. The sauces are bland meat not tender and house wine came from a Large jug or box. Nothing Italian about this place but the name!

The only reason I am even giving this 1 star is because the food wasn't that bad. The reason for this review is because the service was absolutely terrible. From the moment we walked into the door to now, sitting at the table finishing my wine, the service was horrendous.  This was my boyfriend and I's first restaurant as a couple; this was 6 years ago. I was so excited to return tonight because of this wonderful memory. However, the moment we sat down at our table, the waiter was pushy, urgent, and unpleasant. When I asked for the specials, he rapidly repeated them. I did not and could not hear him, so I politely asked him to repeat the last thing he said, which he became very annoyed. I ended up walking downstairs, to the specials board, to be informed of the specials.  It gets worse. He rushed our order, rushed our eating, and never came to our table once during the "meal". Thats okay, because I ended up getting everything I needed from the service station behind me.  When he dropped the check, there was no "thank you have a nice day", nothing. Not even eye contact. I said "thank you, have a good night" as he was walking away. Every single thing the waiter did, or lack there of, is an example of things not to do as a server at a restaurant. My boyfriend and I have 15 years of restaurant experience. If training new servers, I would use him as the example of the epitome of a terrible server. He was that bad. That bad for me to waste 10 minutes writing this review. This was such a disappointment because this restaurant was such a great memory to my boyfriend and I. We now are left with the memory of one of the worst waiters ever experienced.  Thanks for that Pines of Rome.

My husband took me here on our first date in June 1989. He lived in Virginia and I lived in DC and I couldn't figure out why he was taking me all the way to Bethesda unless the place was really cheap. The meal was in fact reasonably priced but the God was amazing - we shared the white pizza and I had chicken cacciatore which I promptly spilled on my white blouse. We came back to Pines many times over the years and the food was always delicious.  My husband passed away a year and a half ago and I went back last November to celebrate his birthday - this time I had the eggplant Parmesan and a cannoli. Everything was the same and as delicious as it had been 27 years ago even though my husband wasn't there to enjoy iy. I will always have a soft spot for this place.

Used to work a block over this was one of my favorite places to eat. It is a bit shabby but the food was always awesome. I'm so glad it has survived all of the building around it.

Felt very old.  I did not like wine being served in the same plastic cups used for water.  Strange.  Left me with a bad taste for the wine.  We had a small pizza and it was good.  The decor/atmosphere looks and feels old.  I would not come back again.
Their pizzas are unique and delicious -- I've been going for decades.

Food was alright. When you find a place like this (mom & pop) the hope is that is you found a "gem" outside of the normal trafficked area. While the food was good, it was light in he wow factor. The prices are in the norm for the area (20$/plate). If your looking to impress friends/family from out of the area, look elsewhere.
Favorite landmark in Bethesda, Md. Amazingly good and authentic Italian food. Best white pizza ever.
I used to come here as a little kid and this place has become my favorite place to eat at whenever I'm in town.

This is, hands down, my favorite restaurant. It doesn't look like much when you enter it, but I have never had better comfort food. To be fair, i was raised on this restaurant. I probably went there 2-3 times a month with my family growing up. Their white pizza with cheese is my favorite pizza in the world. be warned, it's greasy. but it's greasy in the most delightful delicious decadent way. This place isn't fancy and it might not impress your foodie friends, but I could eat here daily.
Authentic Italian food and reasonable prices.
Nice family Italian restaurant.
Best White Pizza, Veal Fran., fried zucchini  I have ever eaten.   Food is truly excellent. My favorite restaurant for more than 25 years.
Best home style Italian food in the dc area I

As a NYC resident I am really amazed at the quality and taste of this restaurant. The pasta sauce is truly divine and not oily, very unique. Had broiled red snapper that was superb. It is kid friendly and highly recommended this place.

Worst Italian restaurant I've ever visited. I only go to places with better ratings but my friends wanted to try this place and we were all disappointed.  Food- I had veal veal parmigiana that the meat was dry, flavorless, and overcooked. The spaghetti was undercooked and was chewy and the sauce was bland/flavorless and tasted like poor quality canned sauce. My friends dishes were the same quality.  Service- TERRIBLE. Never checked on us after we ordered until to give us our check. Stood around in sight and gave us eye contact and never came over.  Decor- Poor. Old, dingy, dirty, outdated.

Pretty blah food. Dishes tend to be heavy, greasy, and bland. People rave about this place but I find those that do have been coming here since their childhood. To everyone else it's a dumpy old place with big sloppy portions of blah, disappointing food. The space is big and falling to pieces; the bathrooms are on par with those at a gas station. Service is rushed and indifferent.

I have been going to this place for years and they never fail me. The one thing i always loved is how the lighting is not bright which gives it a romantic feel to it. Food is always fantastic!!! (Get the Ravioli or the lasagna) the portions are huge!

You have to know what to get here. The eggplant parmigiana, cheese and tomato pizza with mushrooms, and cheese ravioli are almost always excellent. I've only had the cheeseless white pizza once, but that was rather good too. The flounder, on the other hand, is consistently overcooked. Salads are definitely weak, although the "family size" salad isn't bad if you have sharers. Wine comes in large portions, if you like that. Another commenter mentioned the bread, which is inconsistent in quality—when it's fresh, it's good.
